							"text": "Poster Abstract: Landing-Type Aware Multi-Drone Route Generation for Last-Mile Delivery Service",
							"articleLocation": "pdfs/ICCPS2024-1FkhQC4Dfn57pDzqp6O87q/692700a281/692700a281.pdf",
							"extraLocations": [],
							"authorNames": "JiHyun Kwon (DGIST, South Korea), BaekGyu Kim (DGIST, South Korea), Yi-Ying Chen (National Taiwan University, Taiwan), Chung-Wei Lin (National Taiwan University, Taiwan)",
							"abstract": "We consider the problem of generating delivery routes for multiple drones in the last-mile delivery service. In particular, the landing type-how a parcel is to be dropped off from a drone-is explicitly modeled in terms of the landing area and the landing time, which was not considered in other drone delivery works. A Mixed Integer Linear Programming (MILP) problem is formulated to optimize the delivery route for each drone by minimizing the total delivery completion time. Our preliminary result shows that landing types affect the total delivery completion time significantly, even with a small number of drones. Therefore, it is necessary to explicitly consider the characteristics of landing types for more realistic delivery route generation of a large number of drones. ",
							"searchText": "2024 ACM/IEEE 15th International Conference on Cyber-Physical Systems (ICCPS) ICCPS 2024 Poster Abstract: Landing-Type Aware Multi-Drone Route Generation for Last-Mile Delivery Service 1709709529312 10.1109/ICCPS61052.2024.00036 JiHyun Kwon DGIST, South Korea jihyun.kwon@dgist.ac.kr BaekGyu Kim DGIST, South Korea bkim@dgist.ac.kr Yi-Ying Chen National Taiwan University, Taiwan r12944016@csie.ntu.edu.tw Chung-Wei Lin National Taiwan University, Taiwan cwlin@csie.ntu.edu.tw Drone delivery Route Planning Landing type Mixed Integer Linear Programming (MILP) We consider the problem of generating delivery routes for multiple drones in the last-mile delivery service. In particular, the landing type-how a parcel is to be dropped off from a drone-is explicitly modeled in terms of the landing area and the landing time, which was not considered in other drone delivery works. A Mixed Integer Linear Programming (MILP) problem is formulated to optimize the delivery route for each drone by minimizing the total delivery completion time. Our preliminary result shows that landing types affect the total delivery completion time significantly, even with a small number of drones. Therefore, it is necessary to explicitly consider the characteristics of landing types for more realistic delivery route generation of a large number of drones.",
