							"authorNames": "Tushar Dilip Kurne (Indian Institute of Science, India), Manas Sashank Juvvi (Indian Institute of Science, India), Vaishnavi J (Indian Institute of Science, India), Pushpak Jagtap (Indian Institute of Science, India)",
							"abstract": "This work proposes a novel approach for model-free motion planning in autonomous robots, with a specific emphasis on handling signal temporal logic (STL) tasks. The approach is structured into two main phases: first, we learn spatio-temporal motion primitives to encapsulate the inherent robot-specific constraints effectively. Subsequently, by utilizing these learned motion primitives, we conduct STL-compliant motion planning. To learn spatiotemporal motion primitives, we leverage reinforcement learning to construct a library of simple motion primitives. Following this, Gaussian process regression is employed to establish mappings from learned motion primitives to spatio-temporal characteristics. Subsequently, we present an STL-compliant motion planning strategy designed to meet the STL specification. Notably, the proposed framework is entirely model-free and capable of generating feasible STL-compliant motion plans across a diverse range of environments.",
							"searchText": "2024 ACM/IEEE 15th International Conference on Cyber-Physical Systems (ICCPS) ICCPS 2024 Poster Abstract: Signal Temporal Logic Compliant Motion Planning using Reinforcement Learning 1709896436514 10.1109/ICCPS61052.2024.00037 Tushar Dilip Kurne Indian Institute of Science, India tusharkurne@iisc.ac.in Manas Sashank Juvvi Indian Institute of Science, India manasjuvvi@iisc.ac.in Vaishnavi J Indian Institute of Science, India vaishnavij@iisc.ac.in Pushpak Jagtap Indian Institute of Science, India pushpak@iisc.ac.in Signal Temporal Logic Path Planning Reinforcement Learning This work proposes a novel approach for model-free motion planning in autonomous robots, with a specific emphasis on handling signal temporal logic (STL) tasks. The approach is structured into two main phases: first, we learn spatio-temporal motion primitives to encapsulate the inherent robot-specific constraints effectively. Subsequently, by utilizing these learned motion primitives, we conduct STL-compliant motion planning. To learn spatiotemporal motion primitives, we leverage reinforcement learning to construct a library of simple motion primitives. Following this, Gaussian process regression is employed to establish mappings from learned motion primitives to spatio-temporal characteristics. Subsequently, we present an STL-compliant motion planning strategy designed to meet the STL specification. Notably, the proposed framework is entirely model-free and capable of generating feasible STL-compliant motion plans across a diverse range of environments.",
