							"text": "A Signal Injection Attack Against Zero Involvement Pairing and Authentication for the Internet of Things",
							"articleLocation": "pdfs/DESTION2024-6m2GWqRzDS06lEv9TYTIdh/759400a009/759400a009.pdf",
							"extraLocations": [],
							"authorNames": "Isaac Ahlgren (Loyola University Chicago), Jack West (University of Wisconsin-Madision), Kyuin Lee (University of Houston), George Thiruvathukal (Loyola University Chicago), Neil Klingensmith (Loyola University Chicago)",
							"abstract": "Zero Involvement Pairing and Authentication (ZIPA) is a promising technique for autoprovisioning large networks of Internet-of-Things (IoT) devices.  In this work, we present the first successful signal injection attack on a ZIPA system. Most existing ZIPA systems assume there is a negligible amount of influence from the unsecured outside space on the secured inside space. In reality, environmental signals do leak from adjacent unsecured spaces and influence the environment of the secured space. Our attack takes advantage of signal injection attack on the popular Schurmann and Sigg algorithm. The keys generated by the adversary with a signal injection attack at 95 dBA is within the standard error of the legitimate device.",
							"searchText": "2024 IEEE Workshop on Design Automation for CPS and IoT (DESTION) DESTION 2024 A Signal Injection Attack Against Zero Involvement Pairing and Authentication for the Internet of Things 1710896921775 10.1109/DESTION62938.2024.00008 Isaac Ahlgren Loyola University Chicago iahlgren@luc.edu Jack West University of Wisconsin-Madision jwwest@wisc.edu Kyuin Lee University of Houston klee48@central.uh.edu George Thiruvathukal Loyola University Chicago gkt@cs.luc.edu Neil Klingensmith Loyola University Chicago neil@cs.luc.edu Internet of Things (IoT) Cybersecurity Zero Involvement Pairing and Authentication Zero Involvement Pairing and Authentication (ZIPA) is a promising technique for autoprovisioning large networks of Internet-of-Things (IoT) devices. In this work, we present the first successful signal injection attack on a ZIPA system. Most existing ZIPA systems assume there is a negligible amount of influence from the unsecured outside space on the secured inside space. In reality, environmental signals do leak from adjacent unsecured spaces and influence the environment of the secured space. Our attack takes advantage of signal injection attack on the popular Schurmann and Sigg algorithm. The keys generated by the adversary with a signal injection attack at 95 dBA is within the standard error of the legitimate device.",
