							"eid": "wyB9mdceJOeK4EGQkWtBW",
							"type": "authorPaper",
							"text": "VIAssist: Adapting Multi-modal Large Language Models for Users with Visual Impairments",
							"articleLocation": "pdfs/FMSys2024-66mI9I70r2x0eBfwXqt81b/634500a032/634500a032.pdf",
							"extraLocations": [],
							"authorNames": "Bufang Yang (The Chinese University of Hong Kong), Lixing He (The Chinese University of Hong Kong), Kaiwei Liu (The Chinese University of Hong Kong), Zhenyu Yan (The Chinese University of Hong Kong)",
							"abstract": "Individuals with visual impairments, encompassing both partial and total difficulties in visual perception, are referred to as visually impaired (VI) people. An estimated 2.2 billion individuals worldwide are affected by visual impairments. Recent advancements in multi-modal large language models (MLLMs) have showcased their extraordinary capabilities across various domains. It is desirable to help VI individuals with MLLMs' great capabilities of visual understanding and reasoning. However, it is challenging for VI people to use MLLMs due to the difficulties in capturing the desirable images to fulfill their daily requests. For example, the target object is not fully or partially placed in the image. This paper explores how to leverage MLLMs for VI individuals to provide visual-question answers. VIAssist can identify undesired images and provide detailed actions. Finally, VIAssist can provide reliable answers to users' queries based on the images. Our results show that VIAssist provides +0.21 and +0.31 higher BERTScore and ROUGE scores than the baseline, respectively.",
							"searchText": "2024 IEEE International Workshop on Foundation Models for Cyber-Physical Systems & Internet of Things (FMSys) FMSys 2024 VIAssist: Adapting Multi-modal Large Language Models for Users with Visual Impairments 1710852129008 10.1109/FMSys62467.2024.00010 Bufang Yang The Chinese University of Hong Kong bfyang@link.cuhk.edu.hk Lixing He The Chinese University of Hong Kong 1155170464@link.cuhk.edu.hk Kaiwei Liu The Chinese University of Hong Kong 1155189693@link.cuhk.edu.hk Zhenyu Yan The Chinese University of Hong Kong zyyan@ie.cuhk.edu.hk Visual impairments Foundation models Visual question answering Multi-modal large language models (MLLMs) Internet of Things Individuals with visual impairments, encompassing both partial and total difficulties in visual perception, are referred to as visually impaired (VI) people. An estimated 2.2 billion individuals worldwide are affected by visual impairments. Recent advancements in multi-modal large language models (MLLMs) have showcased their extraordinary capabilities across various domains. It is desirable to help VI individuals with MLLMs' great capabilities of visual understanding and reasoning. However, it is challenging for VI people to use MLLMs due to the difficulties in capturing the desirable images to fulfill their daily requests. For example, the target object is not fully or partially placed in the image. This paper explores how to leverage MLLMs for VI individuals to provide visual-question answers. VIAssist can identify undesired images and provide detailed actions. Finally, VIAssist can provide reliable answers to users' queries based on the images. Our results show that VIAssist provides +0.21 and +0.31 higher BERTScore and ROUGE scores than the baseline, respectively.",
							"pageNumber": 32,
