							"extraLocations": [],
							"authorNames": "Yixin Li (North Carolina State University, USA), Ning Sui (North Carolina State University, USA), Chenhan Xu (North Carolina State University, USA), Anil Gehi (UNC School of Medicine, USA), Zhishan Guo (North Carolina State University, USA)",
							"abstract": "Addressing the critical challenge of timely cardiovascular disease detection outside hospital settings, our research proposes an innovative real-time detection system utilizing abnormal Electrocardiogram (ECG) cycles on embedded systems. By selectively analyzing ECG cycles indicative of heart abnormalities with a lightweight neural network, we drastically reduce computational demands while ensuring high diagnostic accuracy. This method represents a significant shift from traditional cloud-based analyses, overcoming limitations like communication service reachability in remote areas. Our preliminary findings, based on the PhysioNet 2021 Challenge dataset, demonstrate that our approach not only achieves superior diagnostic performance but also presents a viable solution for integrating advanced cardiac monitoring into wearable devices, offering a promising avenue for enhancing out-of-hospital cardiac care.",
							"searchText": "2024 23rd ACM/IEEE International Conference on Information Processing in Sensor Networks (IPSN) IPSN 2024 Poster Abstract: Real-Time Cardiovascular Disease Detection via Abnormal Electrocardiogram Cycles on Embedded Systems 1711660614796 10.1109/IPSN61024.2024.00044 Yixin Li North Carolina State University, USA yli223@ncsu.edu Ning Sui North Carolina State University, USA nsui@ncsu.edu Chenhan Xu North Carolina State University, USA cxu34@ncsu.edu Anil Gehi UNC School of Medicine, USA anil_gehi@med.unc.edu Zhishan Guo North Carolina State University, USA zguo32@ncsu.edu Deep Learning ECG Signal Processing Real-time System Addressing the critical challenge of timely cardiovascular disease detection outside hospital settings, our research proposes an innovative real-time detection system utilizing abnormal Electrocardiogram (ECG) cycles on embedded systems. By selectively analyzing ECG cycles indicative of heart abnormalities with a lightweight neural network, we drastically reduce computational demands while ensuring high diagnostic accuracy. This method represents a significant shift from traditional cloud-based analyses, overcoming limitations like communication service reachability in remote areas. Our preliminary findings, based on the PhysioNet 2021 Challenge dataset, demonstrate that our approach not only achieves superior diagnostic performance but also presents a viable solution for integrating advanced cardiac monitoring into wearable devices, offering a promising avenue for enhancing out-of-hospital cardiac care.",
