							"extraLocations": [],
							"authorNames": "Qipeng Xie (Zhejiang Lab, HangZhou, China; PQC Technologies Limited, China; Hong Kong University of Science and Technology, China), Zhihe Zhao (ThingX Technologies Limited, Hong Kong SAR; Chinese University of Hong Kong, Hong Kong SAR), Linshan Jiang (National University of Singapore, Singapore), Siyang Jiang (Chinese University of Hong Kong, Hong Kong SAR), Salabat Khan (Hong Kong University of Science and Technology, China), Weizheng Wang (City University of Hong Kong, Hong Kong SAR), Kaishun Wu (Hong Kong University of Science and Technology, China)",
							"abstract": "With the advancement of the Internet of Medical Things (IoMT) and cryptographic technologies, remote healthcare services have become more widespread, presenting new challenges for patient privacy and data security. Conventional security mechanisms, such as centralized authentication and key distribution systems, are susceptible to single points of failure and significant management burdens, potentially leading to compromised authentication centers and internal security threats. In response, this study presents a threshold signature algorithm, it uses Distributed Key Generation (DKG) that distributes private keys without the need for a trusted key distributor, requiring the cooperative signature of at least two nodes for authentication. This approach not only circumvents the risk of single points of failure but also enhances the system's robustness and efficiency. The experimental results validate its prospective utility in safeguarding remote healthcare data.",
							"searchText": "2024 23rd ACM/IEEE International Conference on Information Processing in Sensor Networks (IPSN) IPSN 2024 Poster Abstract: Threshold Cryptography-Based Authentication Protocol for Remote Healthcare 1711976709716 10.1109/IPSN61024.2024.00052 Qipeng Xie Zhejiang Lab, HangZhou, China; PQC Technologies Limited, China; Hong Kong University of Science and Technology, China n/a Zhihe Zhao ThingX Technologies Limited, Hong Kong SAR; Chinese University of Hong Kong, Hong Kong SAR n/a Linshan Jiang National University of Singapore, Singapore n/a Siyang Jiang Chinese University of Hong Kong, Hong Kong SAR n/a Salabat Khan Hong Kong University of Science and Technology, China n/a Weizheng Wang City University of Hong Kong, Hong Kong SAR n/a Kaishun Wu Hong Kong University of Science and Technology, China n/a Threshold Cryptography Authentication Protocol IoMT With the advancement of the Internet of Medical Things (IoMT) and cryptographic technologies, remote healthcare services have become more widespread, presenting new challenges for patient privacy and data security. Conventional security mechanisms, such as centralized authentication and key distribution systems, are susceptible to single points of failure and significant management burdens, potentially leading to compromised authentication centers and internal security threats. In response, this study presents a threshold signature algorithm, it uses Distributed Key Generation (DKG) that distributes private keys without the need for a trusted key distributor, requiring the cooperative signature of at least two nodes for authentication. This approach not only circumvents the risk of single points of failure but also enhances the system's robustness and efficiency. The experimental results validate its prospective utility in safeguarding remote healthcare data.",
