							"type": "authorPaper",
							"text": "Safe and Secure? On the Timing Analysability of Cryptographic Implementations",
							"articleLocation": "pdfs/RTAS2024-2YY4oP4nFEPkTHWM9dDUYo/584100a068/584100a068.pdf",
							"extraLocations": [],
							"authorNames": "Alexander Stegmeier (University of Augsburg, Germany), Peter Knauer (Augsburg Technical University of Applied Sciences, Germany), Philipp Schubaur (Augsburg Technical University of Applied Sciences, Germany), Christian Piatka (University of Augsburg, Germany), Dominik Merli (Augsburg Technical University of Applied Sciences, Germany), Sebastian Altmeyer (University of Augsburg, Germany)",
							"abstract": "Hard real-time systems are increasingly vulnerable to cyberattacks. Since real-time systems represent a significant proportion of safety-critical systems not only established safety standards but also security standards have to be considered. In particular, standard cryptographic libraries are required to reach an adequate level of protection. In this study, we investigate whether it is possible to ensure security and hard real-time without compromising either side. Thus, we examine relevant state-of-the-art cryptographic primitives provided by one of the de-facto standard libraries Mbed TLS, which is widely-used in embedded systems. We investigate the possibility to derive a Worst-Case Execution Time (WCET) for these primitives and review the code base with regard to compliance on safety related coding guidelines. In addition, we assess the relevant aspects when security concerns must be considered in the safety related context. Our research reveals several obstacles to fully apply Mbed TLS in hard real-time systems.",
							"searchText": "2024 IEEE 30th Real-Time and Embedded Technology and Applications Symposium (RTAS) RTAS 2024 Safe and Secure? On the Timing Analysability of Cryptographic Implementations 1709557218208 10.1109/RTAS61025.2024.00014 Alexander Stegmeier University of Augsburg, Germany stegmeier@es-augsburg.de Peter Knauer Augsburg Technical University of Applied Sciences, Germany peter.knauer@hs-augsburg.de Philipp Schubaur Augsburg Technical University of Applied Sciences, Germany philipp.schubaur@hs-augsburg.de Christian Piatka University of Augsburg, Germany piatka@es-augsburg.de Dominik Merli Augsburg Technical University of Applied Sciences, Germany dominik.merli@hs-augsburg.de Sebastian Altmeyer University of Augsburg, Germany altmeyer@es-augsburg.de Security Safety Real-Time Cryptography Static timing analysis Hard real-time systems are increasingly vulnerable to cyberattacks. Since real-time systems represent a significant proportion of safety-critical systems not only established safety standards but also security standards have to be considered. In particular, standard cryptographic libraries are required to reach an adequate level of protection. In this study, we investigate whether it is possible to ensure security and hard real-time without compromising either side. Thus, we examine relevant state-of-the-art cryptographic primitives provided by one of the de-facto standard libraries Mbed TLS, which is widely-used in embedded systems. We investigate the possibility to derive a Worst-Case Execution Time (WCET) for these primitives and review the code base with regard to compliance on safety related coding guidelines. In addition, we assess the relevant aspects when security concerns must be considered in the safety related context. Our research reveals several obstacles to fully apply Mbed TLS in hard real-time systems.",
