							"type": "authorPaper",
							"text": "Brief Industry Paper: Delay-Aware Control in Networked Systems using Smart Actuators",
							"articleLocation": "pdfs/RTAS2024-2YY4oP4nFEPkTHWM9dDUYo/584100a396/584100a396.pdf",
							"extraLocations": [],
							"authorNames": "Paolo Pazzaglia (Robert Bosch GmbH, Corporate Research), Christoph Mark (Robert Bosch GmbH, Corporate Research), Behnaz Pourmohseni (Robert Bosch GmbH, Corporate Research), Fedor Smirnov (Robert Bosch GmbH, Corporate Research), Kevin Schmidt (Robert Bosch GmbH, Corporate Research), Laura Beermann (Robert Bosch GmbH, Corporate Research)",
							"abstract": "The control applications of the future will increasingly rely on edge and cloud services to access enhanced computational resources, boosting efficiency and optimizing performance. Such networked systems are however sensitive to variable delays, which are inevitably introduced by the communication between the plant and the remote controller. To increase reliability, we present a delay-aware control design, based on the execution of multiple control modes optimized for different latency conditions, paired with a smart actuator that measures the control chain delay at runtime. The delay information is used by the actuator to select the best suited control input for the current delay, resulting in a higher performance of the control application. Additionally, the measured delay can be used in feedback to adjust the controller configuration for the subsequent iterations.",
							"searchText": "2024 IEEE 30th Real-Time and Embedded Technology and Applications Symposium (RTAS) RTAS 2024 Brief Industry Paper: Delay-Aware Control in Networked Systems using Smart Actuators 1709909287753 10.1109/RTAS61025.2024.00041 Paolo Pazzaglia Robert Bosch GmbH, Corporate Research paolo.pazzaglia@de.bosch.com Christoph Mark Robert Bosch GmbH, Corporate Research christoph.mark@de.bosch.com Behnaz Pourmohseni Robert Bosch GmbH, Corporate Research behnaz.pourmohseni@de.bosch.com Fedor Smirnov Robert Bosch GmbH, Corporate Research fedor.smirnov@de.bosch.com Kevin Schmidt Robert Bosch GmbH, Corporate Research kevin.schmidt4@de.bosch.com Laura Beermann Robert Bosch GmbH, Corporate Research laura.beermann@de.bosch.com The control applications of the future will increasingly rely on edge and cloud services to access enhanced computational resources, boosting efficiency and optimizing performance. Such networked systems are however sensitive to variable delays, which are inevitably introduced by the communication between the plant and the remote controller. To increase reliability, we present a delay-aware control design, based on the execution of multiple control modes optimized for different latency conditions, paired with a smart actuator that measures the control chain delay at runtime. The delay information is used by the actuator to select the best suited control input for the current delay, resulting in a higher performance of the control application. Additionally, the measured delay can be used in feedback to adjust the controller configuration for the subsequent iterations.",
