							"type": "authorPaper",
							"text": "Work in Progress: Guaranteeing Weakly-Hard Timing Constraints in Server-Based Real-Time Systems",
							"articleLocation": "pdfs/RTAS2024-2YY4oP4nFEPkTHWM9dDUYo/584100a402/584100a402.pdf",
							"extraLocations": [],
							"authorNames": "Nasim Samimi (Eindhoven University of Technology, The Netherlands), Mitra Nasri (Eindhoven University of Technology, The Netherlands), Twan Basten (Eindhoven University of Technology, The Netherlands), Marc Geilen (Eindhoven University of Technology, The Netherlands)",
							"abstract": "Ensuring deadlines of hard real-time applications in server-based deployments is a challenging problem, particularly if the workload arrives following an arbitrary arrival curve. This work extends the \"(M,K)-firm weakly hard\" model to server-based systems, ensuring timely processing of real-time requests to the server. We introduce an admission policy to regulate the remote server workload and prevent deadline misses while attempting to admit more requests than the minimum required, when possible. We guarantee the weakly hard constraints through optimal resource allocation and server configuration.",
							"searchText": "2024 IEEE 30th Real-Time and Embedded Technology and Applications Symposium (RTAS) RTAS 2024 Work in Progress: Guaranteeing Weakly-Hard Timing Constraints in Server-Based Real-Time Systems 1709976384659 10.1109/RTAS61025.2024.00043 Nasim Samimi Eindhoven University of Technology, The Netherlands n/a Mitra Nasri Eindhoven University of Technology, The Netherlands n/a Twan Basten Eindhoven University of Technology, The Netherlands n/a Marc Geilen Eindhoven University of Technology, The Netherlands n/a Server-based systems admission test response time analysis arrival curve real-time systems Ensuring deadlines of hard real-time applications in server-based deployments is a challenging problem, particularly if the workload arrives following an arbitrary arrival curve. This work extends the \"(M,K)-firm weakly hard\" model to server-based systems, ensuring timely processing of real-time requests to the server. We introduce an admission policy to regulate the remote server workload and prevent deadline misses while attempting to admit more requests than the minimum required, when possible. We guarantee the weakly hard constraints through optimal resource allocation and server configuration.",
