							"eid": "49YKNZtO2bHdvu1iNqnyfe",
							"type": "authorPaper",
							"text": "Intermittent Edge Computing for Green Agricultural Automation",
							"articleLocation": "pdfs/IoTDI2024-45xciEppCNCyxkOl1ds1Qh/702500a219/702500a219.pdf",
							"extraLocations": [],
							"authorNames": "Hui-Xin Shih (Academia Sinica & National Taiwan University, Taiwan), Yu-An Lin (Academia Sinica & National Taiwan University, Taiwan), Hsu-Huai Tsai (Academia Sinica & National Taiwan University, Taiwan), Yuan Lin-Huang (Academia Sinica & National Taiwan University, Taiwan), Chih-Yu Wang (Research Center for Information Technology Innovation, Academia Sinica, Taiwan)",
							"abstract": "In recent years, there has been a notable shift towards automation in agricultural technology. Furthermore, driven by environmental concerns, green energy is gradually replacing conventional power sources. However, green energy sources are vulnerable to external environmental factors, resulting in an unreliable power supply. Such instability can disrupt the functioning of monitoring systems which are critical for agricultural automation, leading to operational issues. To address these challenges, we propose an intermittent edge computing system for agricultural automation. It consists of battery-less intermittent computing devices, wireless intermittent communications, and deep-capable edge computing. Our demo illustrates the process of tomato monitoring including reliable on-device tomato detection and Bluetooth Low Energy (BLE) image data transmission, even in the absence of stable power conditions. Upon receiving the data, we employ edge computing to detect the location, color, and quantity of tomatoes. ",
							"searchText": "2024 IEEE/ACM Ninth International Conference on Internet-of-Things Design and Implementation (IoTDI) IoTDI 2024 Intermittent Edge Computing for Green Agricultural Automation 1711508415107 10.1109/IoTDI61053.2024.00025 Hui-Xin Shih Academia Sinica & National Taiwan University, Taiwan b09901091@ntu.edu.tw Yu-An Lin Academia Sinica & National Taiwan University, Taiwan b06204039@ntu.edu.tw Hsu-Huai Tsai Academia Sinica & National Taiwan University, Taiwan b08902016@ntu.edu.tw Yuan Lin-Huang Academia Sinica & National Taiwan University, Taiwan b09901013@ntu.edu.tw Chih-Yu Wang Research Center for Information Technology Innovation, Academia Sinica, Taiwan cywang@citi.sinica.edu.tw In recent years, there has been a notable shift towards automation in agricultural technology. Furthermore, driven by environmental concerns, green energy is gradually replacing conventional power sources. However, green energy sources are vulnerable to external environmental factors, resulting in an unreliable power supply. Such instability can disrupt the functioning of monitoring systems which are critical for agricultural automation, leading to operational issues. To address these challenges, we propose an intermittent edge computing system for agricultural automation. It consists of battery-less intermittent computing devices, wireless intermittent communications, and deep-capable edge computing. Our demo illustrates the process of tomato monitoring including reliable on-device tomato detection and Bluetooth Low Energy (BLE) image data transmission, even in the absence of stable power conditions. Upon receiving the data, we employ edge computing to detect the location, color, and quantity of tomatoes.",
